1. Purpose

This document specifies the architecture of the Short-Form Indexed Memory Architecture (SIMA).

SIMA is a model-agnostic architecture for persistent AI memory that separates:

Storage Representation

from:

Retrieval Representation

The system is designed around progressive retrieval.

Rather than immediately loading complete memory records into an active model context, SIMA attempts to identify relevant memories using compact retrieval representations and only expands full memory records when necessary.

The architecture is intended to investigate whether this separation can improve:

Retrieval efficiency
Memory scalability
Context efficiency
Long-term recall
Multi-hop recall
Retrieval latency

No performance improvement is assumed without empirical validation.

2. Design Principles

SIMA follows six primary principles.

2.1 Separate storage from retrieval

The representation required to preserve a memory is not necessarily the representation required to find it.

Therefore:

Persistent Memory
